<doc id="431041" wikidata="Q1095056" url="?curid=431041" title="Singular homology">
<text>In algebraic topology, singular homology refers to the study of a certain set of algebraic invariants of a topological space formula_1, the so-called homology groups formula_2 Intuitively, singular homology counts, for each dimension formula_3, the formula_3-dimensional holes of a space. Singular homology is a particular example of a homology theory, which has now grown to be a rather broad collection of theories. Of the various theories, it is perhaps one of the simpler ones to understand, being built on fairly concrete constructions (see also the related theory simplicial homology).

In brief, singular homology is constructed by taking maps of the standard -simplex to a topological space, and composing them into formal sums, called singular chains. The boundary operation – mapping each formula_3-dimensional simplex to its formula_6-dimensional boundary – induces the singular chain complex. The singular homology is then the homology of the chain complex. The resulting homology groups are the same for all homotopy equivalent spaces, which is the reason for their study. These constructions can be applied to all topological spaces, and so singular homology is expressible as a functor from the category of topological spaces to the category of graded abelian groups.

== Singular simplices ==
A singular -simplex in a topological space formula_1 is a continuous function (also called a map) formula_8 from the standard formula_3-simplex formula_10 to formula_1, written formula_12 This map need not be injective, and there can be non-equivalent singular simplices with the same image in formula_1.

The boundary of formula_14 denoted as formula_15 is defined to be the formal sum of the singular formula_6-simplices represented by the restriction of formula_8 to the faces of the standard formula_3-simplex, with an alternating sign to take orientation into account. (A formal sum is an element of the free abelian group on the simplices. The basis for the group is the infinite set of all possible singular simplices. The group operation is &quot;addition&quot; and the sum of simplex formula_19 with simplex formula_20 is usually simply designated formula_21, but formula_22 and so on. Every simplex formula_19 has a negative formula_24.) Thus, if we designate formula_8 by its vertices

:formula_26

corresponding to the vertices formula_27 of the standard formula_3-simplex formula_10 (which of course does not fully specify the singular simplex produced by formula_8), then

:formula_31

is a formal sum of the faces of the simplex image designated in a specific way. (That is, a particular face has to be the restriction of formula_8 to a face of formula_10 which depends on the order that its vertices are listed.) Thus, for example, the boundary of formula_34 (a curve going from formula_35 to formula_36) is the formal sum (or &quot;formal difference&quot;) formula_37.

== Singular chain complex ==
The usual construction of singular homology proceeds by defining formal sums of simplices, which may be understood to be elements of a free abelian group, and then showing that we can define a certain group, the homology group of the topological space, involving the boundary operator.

Consider first the set of all possible singular formula_3-simplices formula_39 on a topological space formula_1. This set may be used as the basis of a free abelian group, so that each singular formula_3-simplex is a generator of the group. This set of generators is of course usually infinite, frequently uncountable, as there are many ways of mapping a simplex into a typical topological space. The free abelian group generated by this basis is commonly denoted as formula_42. Elements of formula_42 are called singular -chains; they are formal sums of singular simplices with integer coefficients.

The boundary formula_44 is readily extended to act on singular formula_3-chains. The extension, called the boundary operator, written as

:formula_46

is a homomorphism of groups. The boundary operator, together with the formula_47, form a chain complex of abelian groups, called the singular complex. It is often denoted as formula_48 or more simply formula_49.

The kernel of the boundary operator is formula_50, and is called the group of singular -cycles. The image of the boundary operator is formula_51, and is called the group of singular -boundaries.

It can also be shown that formula_52, implying formula_53. The formula_3-th homology group of formula_1 is then defined as the factor group

:formula_56

The elements of formula_57 are called homology classes.

== Homotopy invariance ==

If &quot;X&quot; and &quot;Y&quot; are two topological spaces with the same homotopy type (i.e. are homotopy equivalent), then

:formula_58

for all &quot;n&quot; ≥ 0. This means homology groups are homotopy invariants, and therefore topological invariants.

In particular, if &quot;X&quot; is a connected contractible space, then all its homology groups are 0, except formula_59.

A proof for the homotopy invariance of singular homology groups can be sketched as follows. A continuous map &quot;f&quot;: &quot;X&quot; → &quot;Y&quot; induces a homomorphism

:formula_60

It can be verified immediately that

:formula_61

i.e. &quot;f&quot;# is a chain map, which descends to homomorphisms on homology

:formula_62

We now show that if &quot;f&quot; and &quot;g&quot; are homotopically equivalent, then &quot;f&quot;* = &quot;g&quot;*. From this follows that if &quot;f&quot; is a homotopy equivalence, then &quot;f&quot;* is an isomorphism.

Let &quot;F&quot; : &quot;X&quot; × [0, 1] → &quot;Y&quot; be a homotopy that takes &quot;f&quot; to &quot;g&quot;. On the level of chains, define a homomorphism

:formula_63

that, geometrically speaking, takes a basis element σ: Δ&quot;n&quot; → &quot;X&quot; of &quot;Cn&quot;(&quot;X&quot;) to the &quot;prism&quot; &quot;P&quot;(σ): Δ&quot;n&quot; × &quot;I&quot; → &quot;Y&quot;. The boundary of &quot;P&quot;(σ) can be expressed as

:formula_64

So if &quot;α&quot; in &quot;Cn&quot;(&quot;X&quot;) is an &quot;n&quot;-cycle, then &quot;f&quot;#(&quot;α&quot;) and &quot;g&quot;#(&quot;α&quot;) differ by a boundary:

:formula_65

i.e. they are homologous. This proves the claim.

== Homology groups of common spaces ==
The table below shows the k-th homology groups formula_66 of n-dimensional real projective spaces RP&quot;n&quot;, complex projective spaces, CP&quot;n&quot;, a point, spheres &quot;S&quot;n(formula_67), and a 3-torus &quot;T&quot;3 with integer coefficients.
==Functoriality==
The construction above can be defined for any topological space, and is preserved by the action of continuous maps. This generality implies that singular homology theory can be recast in the language of category theory. In particular, the homology group can be understood to be a functor from the category of topological spaces Top to the category of abelian groups Ab.

Consider first that formula_68 is a map from topological spaces to free abelian groups. This suggests that formula_42 might be taken to be a functor, provided one can understand its action on the morphisms of Top. Now, the morphisms of Top are continuous functions, so if formula_70 is a continuous map of topological spaces, it can be extended to a homomorphism of groups

:formula_71

by defining

:formula_72

where formula_73 is a singular simplex, and formula_74 is a singular &quot;n&quot;-chain, that is, an element of formula_42. This shows that formula_47 is a functor

:formula_77

from the category of topological spaces to the category of abelian groups.

The boundary operator commutes with continuous maps, so that formula_78. This allows the entire chain complex to be treated as a functor. In particular, this shows that the map formula_79 is a functor

:formula_80

from the category of topological spaces to the category of abelian groups. By the homotopy axiom, one has that formula_81 is also a functor, called the homology functor, acting on hTop, the quotient homotopy category:

:formula_82

This distinguishes singular homology from other homology theories, wherein formula_81 is still a functor, but is not necessarily defined on all of Top. In some sense, singular homology is the &quot;largest&quot; homology theory, in that every homology theory on a subcategory of Top agrees with singular homology on that subcategory. On the other hand, the singular homology does not have the cleanest categorical properties; such a cleanup motivates the development of other homology theories such as cellular homology.

More generally, the homology functor is defined axiomatically, as a functor on an abelian category, or, alternately, as a functor on chain complexes, satisfying axioms that require a boundary morphism that turns short exact sequences into long exact sequences. In the case of singular homology, the homology functor may be factored into two pieces, a topological piece and an algebraic piece. The topological piece is given by

:formula_84

which maps topological spaces as formula_85 and continuous functions as formula_86. Here, then, formula_87 is understood to be the singular chain functor, which maps topological spaces to the category of chain complexes Comp (or Kom). The category of chain complexes has chain complexes as its objects, and chain maps as its morphisms.

The second, algebraic part is the homology functor

:formula_88

which maps

:formula_89

and takes chain maps to maps of abelian groups. It is this homology functor that may be defined axiomatically, so that it stands on its own as a functor on the category of chain complexes.

Homotopy maps re-enter the picture by defining homotopically equivalent chain maps. Thus, one may define the quotient category hComp or K, the homotopy category of chain complexes.

== Coefficients in &quot;R&quot; ==
Given any unital ring &quot;R&quot;, the set of singular &quot;n&quot;-simplices on a topological space can be taken to be the generators of a free &quot;R&quot;-module. That is, rather than performing the above constructions from the starting point of free abelian groups, one instead uses free &quot;R&quot;-modules in their place. All of the constructions go through with little or no change. The result of this is

:formula_90

which is now an &quot;R&quot;-module. Of course, it is usually &quot;not&quot; a free module. The usual homology group is regained by noting that

:formula_91

when one takes the ring to be the ring of integers. The notation &quot;H&quot;&quot;n&quot;(&quot;X&quot;; &quot;R&quot;) should not be confused with the nearly identical notation &quot;H&quot;&quot;n&quot;(&quot;X&quot;, &quot;A&quot;), which denotes the relative homology (below).

The universal coefficient theorem provides a mechanism to calculate the homology with &quot;R&quot; coefficients in terms of homology with usual integer coefficients using the short exact sequence

